ed on table emptiness and retry lists.","Because these sibling modules expose different helper layers and status conventions for the same domain operation, a developer extending 'raw season WMI' has to relearn the local style instead of following one shared pattern."],"suggestion":"Choose one internal protocol for season calculators: either shared possession-table builders plus a common summary function, or shared per-game component builders plus one retry/status wrapper. Extract the common path into a shared module and make both season entrypoints thin wrappers over that convention.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"flat_script_conventions"},{"dimension":"convention_outlier","identifier":"mixed_sample_and_library_roles","summary":"Sibling single-game modules mix reusable logic and sample-specific workflow assumptions","related_files":["build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py","step2_build_possessions.py"],"evidence":["`build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py` and `categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py` define reusable data-building functions but package them in matchup-specific filenames.","`calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py` is coupled to `possession_model_table_okc_mil.csv` rather than calling shared builders directly, so this sibling module follows a file-based handoff protocol instead of the in-memory helper style used elsewhere.","`step2_build_possessions.py` exposes another reusable function, `parse_possessions`, but its filename reflects a notebook-style sequence step rather than the same domain/output naming used by the other single-game modules."],"suggestion":"Separate reusable modules from demo CLI entrypoints. Keep generic builders in neutrally named modules, and move matchup-specific `main()` wrappers or CSV handoff scripts into a dedicated sample/script layer with consistent names.","confidence":"high","impact